{"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"8d50e484-bb0f-4164-9c6e-72d9fe684289","agentId":"a112f21b5c370ca15","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"Search the web or look at the astropy source code for the CDS (ASCII) unit parsing. The bug is: when reading MRT files with format='ascii.cds', composite units like `10+3J/m/s/kpc2` are incorrectly parsed - `s` ends up in numerator instead of denominator, and `kpc2` ends up in the wrong place too.\n\nSpecifically:\n- Input: `10+3J/m/s/kpc2` → should be `1e3 J / (m s kpc2)` → but gives `1e+3 J s / (kpc2 m)`\n- Input: `10-7J/s/kpc2` → should be `1e-7 J / (s kpc2)` → but gives `1e-7 J kpc2 / s`\n\nLook for astropy source files related to CDS unit parsing. Key files to find:\n1. `astropy/units/format/cds.py` - the CDS unit format parser\n2. `astropy/io/ascii/cds.py` - the CDS ASCII reader\n\nSearch in common Python package locations like:\n- `/usr/lib/python3*/dist-packages/astropy/`\n- `~/.local/lib/python3*/site-packages/astropy/`\n- `/usr/local/lib/python3*/site-packages/astropy/`\n\nFind the actual code that parses the unit string and identify where the bug is. The issue is likely in how `/`-separated unit components are processed - they may be getting reordered or not all treated as divisors.\n\nReport: the file path, the function/method involved, the specific lines causing the bug, and what the fix should be."},"uuid":"74bcacb2-df4f-4f73-b528-62d42f9e176f","timestamp":"2026-05-02T09:02:40.530Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/Users/lysaniuk/Documents/reasoning-scale2-worktrees/t0026_phase2_abc_runtime_n147_for_rq1_rq5","sessionId":"bfd59eba-2a4c-417f-be55-04cfff97e44c","version":"2.1.118","gitBranch":"task/t0026_phase2_abc_runtime_n147_for_rq1_rq5"}
